    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_400631273" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/400631273" />
    <a title="Tom" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/1245181-tom"><img alt="Tom" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1562256827p2/1245181.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/400631273?book_show_action=true">Aug 26, 2012</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Tom" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Tom" href="/user/show/1245181-tom">Tom</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer400631273" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer16104908689048696674">I&apos;d give it 3 and half stars. Despite his experience as protege, Maupassant is no Flaubert (an unfair comparison or expectation, granted). Perhaps Zola with better style? M&apos;s vision of world is certainly as grim and cynical as Z&apos;s. I prefer M&apos;s short stories, by far, but nonetheless, this book was at times a compelling read, for Du Roy&apos;s outrageous machinations and ambitions, which become so appalling that you assume it all has to fall apart and backfire at some point, and M&apos;s ability to create </span>
  <span id="freeText16104908689048696674" style="display:none">I'd give it 3 and half stars. Despite his experience as protege, Maupassant is no Flaubert (an unfair comparison or expectation, granted). Perhaps Zola with better style? M's vision of world is certainly as grim and cynical as Z's. I prefer M's short stories, by far, but nonetheless, this book was at times a compelling read, for Du Roy's outrageous machinations and ambitions, which become so appalling that you assume it all has to fall apart and backfire at some point, and M's ability to create that kind of tension puts him a step above Zola. But the real surprise was M's language, which not only held up better than I expected over course of a novel, but also proved powerfully vivid at times, lyrical at others, as if he felt liberated by working in a looser genre than short story. A prominent death scene was among most unnerving I've read. And his portrayal of high society wedding appears inspired by Flaubert's famous "country fair" scene in Madama Bovary. In the end, though, M's somewhat obvious hand in manipulating these characters to illustrate his attack on corrupt society inhibited my ability or desire to lose myself in the lives of these characters; they were compelling to watch at times, but, with the exception of Madeleine Forestier, an intriguing portrait of intelligent woman forced to practice her talents for writing and politics through lesser men, they never much engaged my sympathies or antipathies.</span>
  <a data-text-id="16104908689048696674" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


